First, the processor finds hits in individual channels. For each ADC waveform segment (“pulse”, see Sect. 2.4), it computes the local baseline and noise level using samples before the self-triggering peak. Next, it searches the pulse for hits, defined as intervals above a threshold equal to or (for high-noise channels) higher than the digitization threshold of ∼\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sim \,$$\end{document}0.3 PE, extended left by 30 ns and right by 200 ns to capture the entire photoelectron signal area.

Second, temporally nearby hits from all channels are clustered. Initially hits are clustered in groups separated by large gaps (2 μ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\upmu $$\end{document}s or more). Next, these groups are split if a local minimum, with significantly higher maxima on either side, occurs in the gain-corrected sum-waveform of the cluster. Finally, further splits are made by a recursive algorithm minimizing intra-cluster variance, up to a level calibrated to not fragment individual signals (as determined on simulated waveforms).

Third, the PAX processor calculates properties for each hit cluster, such as total area, amplitude (in the gain-corrected sum waveform) and various measures of pulse width. The lateral XY-position of the cluster is computed by a likelihood maximizer that works with hitpatterns generated by optical Monte Carlo simulations. The reconstruction algorithm uses the results from simpler methods (maximum PMT, area-weighted mean, etc.) as an initial seed. It was shown in Monte-Carlo studies to have a radial resolution of ΔR≈2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\Delta R\approx 2$$\end{document} cm for the smallest S2 signals in our analysis, improving for larger signals. In addition the algorithm produces confidence contours on the reconstructed position.

The continuous long-term operation of the R11410-21 PMTs in XENON1T started in April 2016, when they were cooled-down in the TPC at a rate of 6 mK/min. The PMTs have remained cold and immersed in LXe for more than 16 months and the majority of tubes showed a stable performance. Instead of aiming for the most uniform gain distribution, the individual bias voltages were chosen to maximize the PMT’s individual single photoelectron (SPE) acceptance. For every PMT the highest stable operation voltage was selected, without exceeding a maximum of -1550\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$-1550$$\end{document} V and a maximum gain of 5×106\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$5 \times 10^6$$\end{document}, to minimize light emission and elevated dark count rates. This optimizes the detector response to low signals and improves the S1 threshold. Individual gain variations are corrected by the data processor (see Sect. 3.2).

The SPE acceptance is defined as the fraction of the SPE peak above the hardware ADC digitization threshold (see Sect. 2.4), which is set to 15 ADC units (=\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
